The field *templatesMap* is accessed via inconsistent synchronization.

Currently the error message returned by DefaultWatcherService does not make sense.
This patch is a bare minimum to fix it:
{noformat}
Index: src/java/com/atlassian/jira/bc/issue/watcher/DefaultWatcherService.java
===================================================================
--- src/java/com/atlassian/jira/bc/issue/watcher/DefaultWatcherService.java	(revision 129548)
+++ src/java/com/atlassian/jira/bc/issue/watcher/DefaultWatcherService.java	(revision )
@@ -120,7 +120,7 @@
         final boolean canView = permissionManager.hasPermission(Permissions.BROWSE, issue, watcher);
         if (!canView)
         {
-            return ServiceOutcomeImpl.error(i18n.getText("watcher.service.error.add.watcher.not.allowed", remoteUser.getName(), issue.getKey()));
+            return ServiceOutcomeImpl.error(i18n.getText("watcher.error.user.cant.see.issue", watcher));
         }

         final boolean canManage = permissionManager.hasPermission(Permissions.MANAGE_WATCHER_LIST, issue, remoteUser);
{noformat}

If you take a closer look at this method and how addWatchers is built, you can see many more problems though:
- permission check should be reversed - first this check:
{code}
        final boolean canManage = permissionManager.hasPermission(Permissions.MANAGE_WATCHER_LIST, issue, remoteUser);
        if (!canManage && !remoteUser.equals(watcher))
        {
            return ServiceOutcomeImpl.error(i18n.getText("watcher.service.error.add.watcher.not.allowed", remoteUser.getName(), issue.getKey()));
        }
{code}
should be done, and only *then* this one:
{code}
        final boolean canView = permissionManager.hasPermission(Permissions.BROWSE, issue, watcher);
        if (!canView)
        {
            return ServiceOutcomeImpl.error(i18n.getText("watcher.error.user.cant.see.issue", watcher));
        }
{code}
Rationale: we don't want to reveal to unauthorized person (to manager watchers) the fact that some other user does not have browser permission. It's a slight security flaw. And web UI does it correctly.
- error messages are not returned to the caller (just the empty {{UNAUTHORIZED()}}).
- HTTP status returned is questionable. 401 is not really true, as the caller _is authorised_, but wants to assign an invalid person (the one which does not have browse issue permissions). Should be rather 400.
- the status code returned actually should depend on the result from {{watcherService.addWatcher(...)}}. As the approach of sending back just string messages is not ideal (no to say stupid) in the service layer (various exceptions depending on what was wrong - similarily to what REST should return - would be IMO better), REST has definitely serious problems (without resorting to analysing error messages from WatcherService - booo...) to send back the correct HTTP status code - 400 for the invalid watcher, 401 for invalid caller (with no permissions)
- last but not least: the caller receives HTML instead of JSON. I haven't taken a deeper look into REST filter chain, but it looks like returning empty response is intercepted and then HTML is returned. When I changed (locally) it to:
{noformat}
            if (!outcome.isValid())
            {
                return UNAUTHORIZED(outcome.getErrorCollection());
            }
{noformat}
then JSON was correctly returned.
It's probably the time to get rid of this empty UNAUTHORIZED() method (used BTW only here in this very method)
